# Swift Build & Compile Hygiene

- Keep the build **warning-clean**; treat new warnings as failures in CI.
- Prefer **small modules/targets** and stable public APIs to reduce incremental build cost.

## Compile-time best practices

- Avoid heavy generic types in public interfaces unless necessary; hide complexity behind protocols/types.
- Prefer `some View` (opaque return types) over giant nested generic view types in signatures.
- Keep files focused; split large types/extensions by feature to improve incremental rebuilds.

## Dependency & target guidance

- Use SwiftPM products/targets with clear boundaries; keep `testTarget`s separate.
- Avoid “umbrella” imports; import the narrowest module you need.

## Xcode settings guidance (when relevant)

- Enable **Dead Code Stripping** for Release.
- Prefer **Whole Module Optimization** for Release; keep Debug optimized minimally for fast iteration.
- Keep `OTHER_SWIFT_FLAGS` minimal; document any non-default flags and why.

## When compilation fails

- Capture the **exact error**, toolchain version, and the minimal file/target set involved.
- Don’t “fix” by silencing errors (e.g., `try?` / `as!`) unless justified with tests and safety.
